are there ways to prevent ear infections in young children is it true that ear plugs while swimming and ear muffs during the winter will stop ear infections or is that an old wives tale water in the ear causes ear canal infection aka swimmers ear that are treated topically with drops middle ear infections are common in younger children due to the eustacian tube some culprits are smoking around children allergies feeding infants by propping bottle middle ear infections need antibiotics taken by mouth also if child has repeated middle ear infections they may be sent to ent and recommend having ventilation tubes placed in the ear the tube allows fluid that accumulates behind ear drum which generally progresses to infection to drain out and reduces the number of infections and pain the placement of tubes is a common procedure and done in the office a lot now also treating the allergies if needed will help if the tubes are used then you cannot allow water to get into the ears to answer your question depends on if you are having middle ear infections or ear canal infections ear muffs never heard of them helping Otitis externa Breastfeeding Pneumonia Swimming Hearing impairment Body piercing Otitis media Common cold Earring Mastoiditis Tuberculosis Prostate cancer Diarrhea Diving Intravenous therapy Glossary of medical terms related to communications disorders Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Asthma Medicine Ear Dialysis Urinary incontinence Tattoo Domestic rabbit Chronic fatigue syndrome Allergy Drowning Route of administration Cat Siphon Group A streptococcal infection First aid Botulism Eustachian tube Cancer Gonorrhoea M__ni__re___s disease Lung cancer Hepatitis C Multiple sclerosis Acute respiratory distress syndrome Conjunctivitis Balance disorder Ear canal Earwax Bong Infant formula Acne Cephalic disorder Diseases of the honeybee Protein-energy malnutrition Gastroesophageal reflux disease Candidiasis Stomach cancer Psoriasis Sickle-cell disease Pelvic inflammatory disease Sch